It seems to have left both a **sensory stain** and an **emotional reflex** that lasted well beyond the period itself.

Most concretely, the experience became attached to **place**. Hamerton says that life at **Ivy Cottage** gave him a **permanent dislike of Shaw and its neighborhood**, so that **even after his father’s death he never went back there willingly**. That suggests the trauma did not remain an abstract memory about “his father”; it adhered to the physical environment — the district itself became charged.

Emotionally, the household trained him into **fear, vigilance, and dread of proximity**. He had come to **fear being left alone with his father**, and his father’s **uncertain moods and greetings** would have made ordinary domestic life feel unstable. In such conditions, a child does not merely suffer isolated bad moments; he learns to live in anticipation, reading tone, manner, and atmosphere for danger.

There is also the misery of the **meals**: they had become **intolerable**, which implies that even routine acts of daily life — sitting at table, conversation, the ceremonial closeness of family life — were contaminated. Trauma often works this way: it invades the ordinary, so that not only dramatic incidents but recurring sensory situations become oppressive.

So long after, the legacy seems to have been:

- **aversion to the place itself**: Shaw remained emotionally poisoned;
- **heightened sensitivity to atmosphere and manner**: his father’s unpredictability made domestic presence itself threatening;
- **association of ordinary household rituals with distress**: even meals became unbearable;
- and more broadly, a lasting sense that **home could be a site of dread rather than safety**.

